This paper is likely to belong to the machine learning (cs.LG) category as it introduces a novel reward-learning-from-observation algorithm that outperforms state-of-the-art imitation learning and inverse reinforcement learning methods on multiple benchmark tasks. It also involves deep reinforcement learning, which is a subfield of machine learning. Additionally, the paper may also belong to the artificial intelligence (cs.AI) and robotics (cs.RO) categories as it deals with inferring intentions and improving performance in tasks. Computer vision (cs.CV) may also be a relevant category as the algorithm involves observing demonstrations. Finally, the paper may also belong to the systems and control (cs.SY) category as it involves improving performance in tasks through reinforcement learning.
